column12: Just a note - he doesn't have difficulty making friends at this age because he is very kind and friendly and active, and he can run around with the best of them. column68: we eat a mostly Mediterranean diet. He loves raw peppers and eats lemons, which I think is a sensory thing. He eats hummus, cucumbers, carrots, tzatziki, spanakopita, avocado sushi, apples, oranges, whole grain pastas with fresh tomatoes and feta cheese and enjoys a good pizza every so often. He also enjoys calamari and salami, but not frequently. He will try anything once, but we stay away from most meats and fried foods and sweets. He does not have juice or milk, just water and seltzer as a treat. He's not a fan of cookies/cake/ice cream, but he almost daily requests Nutella and bananas since I (unfortunately) introduced that to him about a year ago.
column83: The CARS score was a 31, so just above the cutoff. However, the Dev Ped and Neurologist used a number of tests of Michael's IQ that showed him to be very below average. However, since his main problem is his language abilities, we thought it ridiculous to rate his IQ using tests that require verbal responses, and demanded they use the Leiter tests to test his nonverbal IQ. These showed his IQ to be way above-average. But for at least a year before we demanded the new tests, therapists and teachers treated him as if he was way below average, despite our protests. We obtained new tests and new teachers and homeschool him, so we can make sure they are educating him up to his age level, and not at his speaking level, and he is really doing very well academically and socially, even though his speech is still very poor.
